passages.text: Storage Weekly: PSA Walks Away from Abacus Y/Y SS asking rents were up \(+2.0\%\) on avg, a 50 bps improvement from last week's \(+1.5\%\) . On a Y/Y basis, LSI was up \(+4.4\%\) , followed by PSA (+3.0%), EXR (+1.2%), and CUBE (- 0.8%).

PSA Walks Away from Abacus Bid: Earlier this week, PSA announced it had formally withdrawn its A\\$2.17B revised offer for Abacus Storage King after failing to reach agreement with the ASK board on pricing, which remained anchored around NTA of A\\$1.73/share. Recall PSA put in an initial bid of A\\$1.47/share, later raised to A\\$1.65/share, but not before NSR (ASK's largest competitor in Australia) disclosed a \(4.8\%\) stake in ASK.

What's Next for PSA? With Abacus off the table (at least for now), we don't expect PSA to pursue a ground- up build in Australasia, given the time it would take to reach meaningful scale and the challenges of entering a new market without an established platform. Unless another opportunity emerges in Australia, PSA may look at other Asia markets, where several regional portfolios offer exposure across multiple countries with strong demographic tailwinds (an important consideration given the limited size of individual markets and the relatively nascent state of self- storage in many parts of the region).

Using publicly disclosed move- in/out rates and volumes in addition to in- place rents and occupancy, we can back into an ECRI adjustment (a blend of ECRI magnitude and frequency) to SS Revenues on a quarterly/annual basis. Below we use PSA's metrics to illustrate.

What are our Blended & non- blended ECRIs? Non- blended ECRIs measure the impact of two primary factors: 1) The average magnitude of each ECRI sent to existing customers, and 2) the average number of ECRIs sent, which is usually a function of the % of existing customers that are eligible for a rate increase (typically customers that have stayed for >6 months are eligible for one). Blended ECRIs (the metric we use in our models - see here) differ from the non- blended peer in two ways: 1) We do not exclude the impact of discounts (which we think is relatively negligible), and 2) we use the quarterly average rent PSF (rather than the period- end metric).

Not all customers are created equal. Factors that affect the likelihood of receiving a rate hike include: 1) Rent payment relative to Street asking rates; 2) Length of stay; 3) Payment Method (credit card vs check); 4) AutoPay; 5) Store occupancy; 6) Affordability (measured as rent as a % of disposable income); 7) Distance between mailing address and store location (a customer who lives far from his storage unit is less likely to travel back and move to a cheaper unit); 8) Frequency of store visits; 9) Initial booking method (through mobile device vs desktop vs walk- in); 10) Number of competing stores within 1- mile radius.
